iders the comedians' post–civil rights era trajectories, this book is accessibly written and filled with Gregory's and Cosby's original material, appealing to academics, history buffs, and anyone interested in American popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican American entertainersvBiography. 0aAfrican American entertainers. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aAfrican AmericansxSegregationxHumor. 0aCivil rights workerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aCivil rights workerszUnited States. 0aComedianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aComedianszUnited States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : Social and Cultural History. 4aSociology : Social Movements. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847908840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438479088423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438479088/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles